A South Korean lawmaker said communist North Korea could be producing plutonium and could have more secret underground nuclear facilities than already feared.
North Korea has agreed to receive a U.S. delegation next month to discuss American concerns about the construction of a vast underground complex that is widely feared to house a nuclear weapons program.
A congressman who visited remote parts of North Korea last week said that the food and health situation there was desperate and deteriorating, and that millions of North Koreans might have starved to death in the last few years.
